INSERT INTO flashcards (course_id, question_text, answer_text, difficulty, order_index) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the oxygen cascade?', 'The oxygen cascade describes the stepwise fall in oxygen partial pressure (PO2) from ambient air to the mitochondria, where oxygen is used in cellular respiration. Atmospheric PO2 ≈ 21 kPa → alveolar PO2 ≈ 13.5 kPa (after humidification and mixing with CO2) → arterial PO2 ≈ 11–13 kPa → capillary PO2 → mitochondrial PO2 ≈ 0.5–3 kPa. Each step represents resistance to oxygen diffusion. Lung disease, cardiac shunting, or poor perfusion can impair this cascade.', 3, 26),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the difference between hypoxia and hypoxaemia?', 'Hypoxaemia: reduced oxygen concentration in arterial blood — defined as PaO2 <8 kPa or SpO2 <94% (on air). Hypoxia: insufficient oxygen delivery to or utilisation by tissues — the consequence of uncorrected hypoxaemia, anaemia, poor cardiac output, or impaired cellular oxygen use. Hypoxaemia usually causes hypoxia, but hypoxia can occur with a normal SpO2 (e.g. anaemia, CO poisoning). Treating the underlying cause of hypoxia is essential alongside supplemental oxygen.', 2, 27),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the four types of hypoxia?', 'Hypoxic hypoxia: low PaO2 — caused by hypoventilation, V/Q mismatch, shunt, diffusion impairment, or low FiO2 (altitude). Anaemic hypoxia: reduced oxygen-carrying capacity — caused by anaemia or haemoglobin dysfunction (e.g. CO poisoning causing carboxyhaemoglobin). Circulatory (stagnant) hypoxia: reduced blood flow — caused by cardiac failure, shock, or local vascular disease. Histotoxic hypoxia: cells unable to utilise oxygen — caused by cyanide poisoning. Understanding the type guides treatment.', 3, 28),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the signs and symptoms of hypoxia?', 'Early: restlessness, confusion, anxiety, increased respiratory rate, tachycardia. Progressive: cyanosis (central — blue lips and tongue, more reliable than peripheral), laboured breathing, accessory muscle use, hypotension, bradycardia. Severe: unconsciousness, respiratory arrest, cardiac arrest. Note: cyanosis may not be apparent until SpO2 <85% and is unreliable in anaemia or dark skin. Confusion and agitation in any unwell patient should prompt SpO2 measurement.', 2, 29),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the BTS target oxygen saturation ranges and for whom?', 'BTS (British Thoracic Society) guidelines: For most acutely ill patients: target SpO2 94–98%. For patients at risk of hypercapnic respiratory failure (COPD, obesity hypoventilation, chest wall deformities, severe kyphoscoliosis, cystic fibrosis, neuromuscular disorders): target SpO2 88–92%, with target prescribed by a doctor and documented in the notes. In cardiac arrest or CO poisoning: give highest available concentration of oxygen regardless of SpO2.', 2, 30),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What oxygen delivery devices are available and what FiO2 do they provide?', 'Nasal cannula: 1–4 L/min, FiO2 ≈ 24–40%. Simple face mask: 5–10 L/min, FiO2 ≈ 35–50%. Non-rebreather mask (NRM): 10–15 L/min, FiO2 ≈ 60–90% — for emergencies. Venturi mask: precise FiO2 (24%, 28%, 31%, 35%, 40%, 60%) based on coloured barrel — most accurate for COPD patients. High-flow nasal oxygen (HFNO/Optiflow): up to 60 L/min, FiO2 up to 100%, humidified. Oxygen hood (paediatric), incubator. Device choice depends on clinical need and patient tolerance.', 2, 31),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is High Flow Nasal Oxygen (HFNO) and what are its clinical benefits?', 'HFNO (e.g. Optiflow) delivers heated, humidified oxygen at flow rates of 20–60 L/min via nasal cannula, with FiO2 adjustable up to 100%. Benefits: washes out dead space in nasopharynx (improving CO2 clearance), generates modest positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP), is more comfortable than non-rebreather mask or NIV, reduces work of breathing, and improves oxygenation. Indications: hypoxaemic respiratory failure (e.g. COVID-19, pneumonia). Monitor closely for deterioration — HFNO can mask the need for escalation to NIV or intubation.', 3, 32),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'Why is oxygen delivery in COPD with hypercapnic respiratory failure a clinical concern?', 'Patients with chronic hypercapnia may have a hypoxic drive — their respiratory drive partly depends on low PaO2 rather than elevated PaCO2 (which their central chemoreceptors have adapted to). Excessive oxygen in these patients can reduce their respiratory drive, worsen hypoventilation, and cause a further rise in PaCO2 — worsening respiratory acidosis. However, oxygen should never be withheld from a hypoxic patient. Use Venturi mask to deliver precise FiO2 (24–28%) to achieve target SpO2 88–92%, and monitor with ABG.', 3, 33),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'How is oxygen prescribed in the UK?', 'Oxygen is classified as a medicine in the UK and must be prescribed by a registered prescriber (doctor, nurse prescriber, or via PGD) except in emergency situations. The prescription must specify: target SpO2 range, delivery device, and flow rate. In emergencies (cardiac arrest, anaphylaxis, major trauma), oxygen can be given without a prescription. BTS guidelines (2017) and the BNF provide prescribing guidance. Oxygen administration without a prescription (outside emergencies) is not in accordance with NMC or BTS standards.', 2, 34),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'How should oxygen therapy be monitored?', 'Monitor: SpO2 continuously or at minimum every 15 minutes during titration. If the patient is at risk of hypercapnia or is not responding as expected: obtain arterial blood gas (ABG). Document: device used, flow rate, FiO2 (if Venturi), SpO2 achieved, and patient''s clinical response. If SpO2 is above the target range: wean oxygen (reduce flow rate or change to lower FiO2 device) — hyperoxia has adverse effects. Any change to oxygen should be documented with the reason and a re-assessment.', 2, 35),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'How is an arterial blood gas (ABG) interpreted?', 'Steps: (1) pH: <7.35 = acidosis, >7.45 = alkalosis. (2) PaCO2: >6 kPa = respiratory acidosis; <4.7 kPa = respiratory alkalosis. (3) HCO3: <22 mmol/L = metabolic acidosis; >26 mmol/L = metabolic alkalosis. (4) Identify primary disorder. (5) Assess for compensation. (6) PaO2: <8 kPa = hypoxaemia. (7) Base excess: >+2 = metabolic alkalosis; <-2 = metabolic acidosis. Type 1 RF: low PaO2, normal/low PaCO2. Type 2 RF: low PaO2, high PaCO2.', 3, 36),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'When and how should oxygen be humidified?', 'Humidification is required when: high flow rates (>4 L/min via nasal cannula, or any flow via face mask over extended periods), when secretions are tenacious or difficult to clear, via tracheostomy or ET tube (mandatory), HFNO (built-in heated humidifier). Humidification prevents drying of mucous membranes, ciliary impairment, and mucus plugging. Cold water bubble-through humidifiers are used at low flows; heated water humidifiers are used for high-flow and HFNO systems.', 2, 37),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'How should oxygen be weaned?', 'Wean oxygen once the patient''s condition is improving and SpO2 is stable above the lower limit of the target range on current therapy. Step-down the device (e.g. NRM → simple mask → nasal cannula → air). Reduce flow rate in small increments (e.g. 1–2 L/min). Re-check SpO2 5–10 minutes after each reduction. Document wean plan and response. In COPD patients: obtain ABG to confirm absence of hypercapnic respiratory failure before weaning to air. Avoid prolonged unnecessary oxygen use — hyperoxia causes harm.', 2, 38),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the types of home oxygen available in the UK?', 'Long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT): prescribed for patients with chronic hypoxaemia (e.g. COPD, pulmonary fibrosis, heart failure) — typically via oxygen concentrator. Used for ≥15 hours/day at home. Short-burst oxygen therapy (SBOT): for relief of acute breathlessness using portable cylinder. Ambulatory oxygen therapy: portable concentrator or lightweight cylinder used during exercise and activities outside the home. All are prescribed following formal assessment (including ABG) by a specialist, via the Home Oxygen Service (COMPASS in England).', 2, 39),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What fire safety precautions are required with oxygen?', 'Oxygen greatly accelerates combustion. Safety precautions: no smoking near oxygen equipment, keep oxygen cylinders away from sources of heat, flames, and electrical equipment (minimum 2 metres). Store cylinders securely upright. Do not use oil, grease, or solvent-based products near oxygen equipment. Fire safety advice must be given to all patients on home oxygen. Notify the local fire service of home oxygen use (the Gas Safe/oxygen supplier does this). Cylinders must be stored in a ventilated area. Check equipment for damage regularly.', 2, 40),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the MHRA safety guidance on oxygen?', 'The MHRA has issued guidance on: safe use of oxygen cylinders (correct storage, handling, and labelling), oxygen flowmeter accuracy (calibration required), and risks of oxygen in the perioperative setting. MHRA alerts have highlighted: explosion risk from oxygen in the presence of grease/oil, risks of inappropriate oxygen delivery during patient transport, and the need for designated oxygen equipment not used for other compressed gases. All oxygen equipment must be maintained and serviced as per manufacturer and MHRA guidance.', 2, 41),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is oxygen toxicity and the Lorrain Smith effect?', 'Oxygen toxicity occurs when high concentrations of oxygen (FiO2 >0.6 for prolonged periods) cause reactive oxygen species (free radicals) to damage lung tissue. The Lorrain Smith effect (pulmonary oxygen toxicity) causes tracheobronchitis, alveolar collapse, and diffuse alveolar damage with a clinical picture resembling ARDS. Higher FiO2 over shorter periods can also cause retinal damage in premature neonates (retinopathy of prematurity). Target SpO2 ranges (94–98%) help prevent unnecessary hyperoxia and oxygen toxicity.', 3, 42),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the limitations of pulse oximetry in different clinical conditions?', 'Pulse oximetry (SpO2) measures the proportion of oxyhaemoglobin and therefore may be inaccurate in: CO poisoning (carboxyhaemoglobin reads as oxyhaemoglobin, SpO2 appears falsely normal), methaemoglobinaemia (SpO2 reads approximately 85% regardless of true saturation), severe anaemia (adequate SpO2 despite low oxygen content), poor peripheral perfusion (shock, hypothermia), dark skin pigmentation (overestimation — MHRA 2021 alert), nail varnish (particularly dark or blue colours), and motion artefact.', 3, 43),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the role of capnography as adjunct monitoring to pulse oximetry?', 'Capnography (waveform or continuous end-tidal CO2 monitoring, EtCO2) measures exhaled CO2, providing information about ventilation that SpO2 cannot. It detects: hypoventilation (rising EtCO2) before desaturation occurs, apnoea (flat trace), correct endotracheal tube placement (confirms tracheal intubation), and response to airway management. In sedated patients and those at risk of hypoventilation (opioids, procedural sedation, COPD), capnography is recommended alongside SpO2. Normal EtCO2: 4.5–6.0 kPa.', 3, 44),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the role of oxygen therapy in palliative care?', 'Oxygen in palliative care should be used to relieve hypoxaemia-related symptoms (breathlessness, confusion, restlessness) in patients with documented hypoxaemia (SpO2 <90%). Evidence shows that oxygen does not reduce breathlessness in non-hypoxaemic patients — a fan directed at the face is more effective for the sensation of breathlessness. Oxygen can be burdensome (noise of concentrator, restricting mobility, mask discomfort). Goals of care and patient preference should guide use. Document rationale and review regularly.', 3, 45),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What must be documented when administering oxygen therapy?', 'Documentation must include: prescription for oxygen (or clinical reason for emergency use without prescription), device used, flow rate (L/min), FiO2 if using Venturi mask, target SpO2, actual SpO2 achieved, time started, any dose/device changes and reason, ABG results if performed, patient response, and who gave or changed the oxygen. Changes to oxygen without documentation are unsafe and could constitute a medication administration error. Electronic observation systems prompt oxygen documentation as part of NEWS2.', 1, 46),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'How should changes to oxygen therapy be communicated within the clinical team?', 'Oxygen changes must be communicated via: updating the prescription chart/electronic prescribing system (change device, flow, target), verbal handover using SBAR, entry in the nursing and medical notes, and updating the observation chart. Changes in oxygen requirements (increasing or decreasing) are clinically significant and must be documented and communicated to the responsible clinician. Reduction in oxygen requirements is a positive sign of recovery; an increase is a deterioration indicator that may trigger an escalation response.', 2, 47),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What are the minimum flow rates required for different oxygen masks to prevent CO2 rebreathing?', 'Minimum flow rates: Simple face mask — minimum 5 L/min (below this, CO2 can accumulate in the mask and be rebreathed). Non-rebreather mask — minimum 10–15 L/min to keep the reservoir bag inflated. Partial rebreather mask — minimum 6 L/min. Nasal cannula — 1–4 L/min (no minimum safety concern for CO2 rebreathing). Venturi mask — flow determined by the colour-coded barrel/adaptor (follow manufacturer instructions). Insufficient flow rates allow rebreathing of exhaled CO2.', 2, 48),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the difference between an oxygen concentrator and an oxygen cylinder for home use?', 'Oxygen concentrator: an electrically powered device that filters nitrogen from room air and delivers concentrated oxygen (typically 87–95% purity). Used for LTOT at home. Unlimited supply while plugged in. Not portable (requires electricity). Oxygen cylinder (compressed gas): portable, can be used during power failures or for ambulatory use. Available in various sizes. Must be managed and reordered via home oxygen service. Combined systems use concentrator at home and portable cylinders for mobility outside the home.', 1, 49),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is type 1 and type 2 respiratory failure and how do they differ?', 'Type 1 respiratory failure (hypoxaemic): PaO2 <8 kPa with normal or low PaCO2. Caused by V/Q mismatch, shunt, or diffusion impairment (e.g. pneumonia, pulmonary oedema, pulmonary embolism). The lungs cannot oxygenate but can still ventilate adequately. Type 2 respiratory failure (hypercapnic/ventilatory): PaO2 <8 kPa AND PaCO2 >6 kPa. Caused by inadequate ventilation (COPD, neuromuscular disease, respiratory muscle fatigue). The lungs cannot remove CO2. Oxygen therapy targets differ between type 1 and type 2.', 3, 50)
INSERT INTO quiz_questions (course_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_option, explanation) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the recommended target SpO2 range for most acutely ill adult patients according to BTS guidelines?', '88–92%', '99–100%', '94–98%', '90–95%', 'C', 'The British Thoracic Society (BTS) guidelines recommend a target SpO2 of 94–98% for most acutely ill adult patients. The 88–92% target is reserved for patients at risk of hypercapnic respiratory failure (e.g. COPD). These targets prevent both hypoxaemia (too low) and hyperoxia (too high), both of which cause harm.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'Which oxygen delivery device provides the most accurate and consistent FiO2?', 'Simple face mask at 8 L/min', 'Nasal cannula at 4 L/min', 'Non-rebreather mask at 15 L/min', 'Venturi mask with a colour-coded barrel', 'D', 'The Venturi mask (or fixed-performance mask) uses the Venturi principle to entrain a precise amount of air and delivers a specific, consistent FiO2 regardless of the patient''s breathing pattern. It is the most accurate low-flow device and is particularly important for COPD patients requiring precise oxygen delivery. The other devices deliver variable FiO2 depending on the patient''s inspiratory flow.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'A patient with known COPD and type 2 respiratory failure has an SpO2 of 96% on 4 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula. What is the most appropriate action?', 'Continue current oxygen as SpO2 is within the normal range', 'Increase oxygen to maintain SpO2 at 98–99%', 'Wean oxygen to achieve a target SpO2 of 88–92% using a Venturi mask, and check ABG', 'Discontinue oxygen immediately as the patient has COPD', 'C', 'In a COPD patient with hypercapnic respiratory failure, the target SpO2 is 88–92%. SpO2 of 96% on oxygen indicates over-oxygenation, which risks suppressing the hypoxic drive and worsening hypercapnia. Oxygen should be weaned and a Venturi mask used for controlled delivery, with an ABG to assess PaCO2.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'In England and Wales, oxygen is classified as which type of substance requiring a prescription?', 'A dietary supplement', 'A controlled drug', 'A medicine', 'A medical device', 'C', 'Oxygen is legally classified as a medicine in England and Wales and must be prescribed by an authorised prescriber except in emergency situations. This classification is important because it requires adherence to prescribing standards, including specifying target SpO2, device, and flow rate, rather than simply giving oxygen empirically.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'An ABG shows: pH 7.28, PaCO2 8.5 kPa, PaO2 7.0 kPa, HCO3 30 mmol/L. What does this represent?', 'Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation', 'Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation', 'Type 2 (ventilatory) respiratory failure with partially compensated respiratory acidosis', 'Type 1 respiratory failure with normal CO2', 'C', 'The pH is acidotic (7.28), PaCO2 is elevated (8.5 kPa — respiratory acidosis), and HCO3 is elevated (30 mmol/L — metabolic compensation). PaO2 is low (7.0 kPa — hypoxaemia). This pattern indicates type 2 (hypercapnic/ventilatory) respiratory failure with partially compensated respiratory acidosis, as seen in decompensated COPD or acute on chronic type 2 respiratory failure.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the primary clinical benefit of High-Flow Nasal Oxygen (HFNO) compared to a standard non-rebreather mask?', 'HFNO delivers a lower FiO2, making it safer in all conditions', 'HFNO washes out nasopharyngeal dead space, provides modest PEEP, and is more comfortable for the patient', 'HFNO is less likely to cause oxygen toxicity than a non-rebreather mask', 'HFNO can be used safely in patients with hypercapnic respiratory failure without risk', 'B', 'HFNO delivers high flow rates (up to 60 L/min) of heated, humidified oxygen through nasal cannulae. Its main benefits are nasopharyngeal dead space washout (improving effective alveolar ventilation), generation of modest positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP, typically 2–5 cmH2O), and significantly improved patient comfort compared to tight-fitting masks.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is oxygen toxicity (Lorrain Smith effect) and how is it prevented?', 'Oxygen causing explosion risk in the clinical environment', 'Pulmonary toxicity from prolonged exposure to high FiO2, causing reactive oxygen species-mediated lung damage', 'Hypercapnia caused by suppression of the hypoxic drive', 'Skin and eye irritation from long-term oxygen use', 'B', 'Oxygen toxicity (Lorrain Smith effect) results from prolonged breathing of high concentrations of oxygen (FiO2 >0.6), which generates reactive oxygen species causing tracheobronchitis and diffuse alveolar damage similar to ARDS. Prevention involves using the lowest FiO2 necessary to achieve the target SpO2 range (94–98% for most patients) and avoiding prolonged hyperoxia.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'A patient on home oxygen has a visitor who smokes. What is the most important safety instruction?', 'Smoking is only risky within 30 cm of the oxygen source', 'Smoking is permitted if done in a separate room with the door closed', 'No smoking in any room where oxygen is in use or stored — oxygen accelerates combustion and causes fire risk', 'A small amount of smoking is acceptable if oxygen is turned off during the cigarette', 'C', 'Oxygen greatly accelerates combustion and creates a significant fire risk. Smoking is absolutely prohibited in any area where oxygen is in use or stored. Patients receiving home oxygen must be clearly counselled about this hazard, including visitors. The home oxygen service and the patient''s fire service should be notified of home oxygen use.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'Which type of home oxygen is used for long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT) and requires at least 15 hours of use per day?', 'Portable oxygen cylinder only', 'Short-burst oxygen therapy cylinder', 'Oxygen concentrator', 'Liquid oxygen system only', 'C', 'Long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT) is delivered via an electrically powered oxygen concentrator at home. It must be used for at least 15 hours per day (ideally ≥16 hours) to achieve the survival benefit shown in clinical trials for patients with chronic hypoxaemia (e.g. COPD with PaO2 ≤7.3 kPa). Cylinders are used for ambulatory or short-burst therapy.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'A patient with suspected carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning has an SpO2 of 98% on room air. How should this result be interpreted?', 'The patient is not hypoxic as SpO2 is normal — observe only', 'SpO2 is unreliable in CO poisoning as carboxyhaemoglobin is read as oxyhaemoglobin by the pulse oximeter — give 100% oxygen immediately and obtain co-oximetry or ABG', 'The SpO2 reading confirms the patient is safe and does not need oxygen', 'Reduce supplemental oxygen to prevent oxygen toxicity', 'B', 'Pulse oximetry cannot distinguish between oxyhaemoglobin and carboxyhaemoglobin, so SpO2 is falsely normal in CO poisoning. The patient may be profoundly hypoxic despite a normal SpO2 reading. Treatment is immediate high-flow oxygen (non-rebreather mask at 15 L/min) to accelerate CO elimination. ABG with co-oximetry (measuring COHb) is needed for definitive assessment.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the minimum flow rate that must be maintained through a simple face mask to prevent CO2 rebreathing?', '1 L/min', '3 L/min', '5 L/min', '8 L/min', 'C', 'A minimum flow rate of 5 L/min must be maintained through a simple face mask to ensure sufficient flushing of exhaled CO2 from the dead space within the mask. At flow rates below 5 L/min, CO2 can accumulate and be rebreathed, leading to hypercapnia. This is a key safety consideration in oxygen delivery.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the role of capnography in monitoring patients receiving opioid analgesia?', 'It measures oxygen saturation more accurately than pulse oximetry', 'It detects hypoventilation and rising CO2 before desaturation occurs on pulse oximetry', 'It identifies analgesic effect and guides dose titration', 'It is only required in mechanically ventilated ICU patients', 'B', 'Capnography detects hypoventilation (rising EtCO2) earlier than pulse oximetry detects desaturation, because SpO2 can remain normal for several minutes after apnoea if the patient was receiving supplemental oxygen. In patients receiving opioids (sedation risk), capnography provides earlier warning of respiratory depression and is recommended as adjunct monitoring in procedural sedation and postoperative recovery.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'Which of the following patients is most likely to have a falsely elevated SpO2 reading despite clinically significant hypoxia?', 'A patient with chronic anaemia (Hb 78 g/L) and SpO2 96%', 'A patient with COPD and SpO2 88%', 'A patient with pneumonia and SpO2 91%', 'A patient with pulmonary oedema and SpO2 94%', 'A', 'A patient with severe anaemia may have an SpO2 of 96% as their remaining haemoglobin is well-oxygenated, but the total oxygen content of blood is critically low due to insufficient haemoglobin to carry oxygen. This is anaemic hypoxia. SpO2 measures saturation of available haemoglobin, not total oxygen content. Clinical assessment and haemoglobin measurement are essential in anaemic patients.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the MHRA''s position on the risk of pulse oximetry in patients with dark skin pigmentation?', 'Dark skin pigmentation has no known effect on pulse oximetry accuracy', 'Pulse oximeters may overestimate oxygen saturation in patients with dark skin pigmentation — clinical assessment should accompany SpO2 readings', 'Pulse oximeters should not be used in patients with dark skin pigmentation', 'A different saturation target should be used for patients with dark skin', 'B', 'A 2021 MHRA alert highlighted that pulse oximeters may overestimate SpO2 in patients with dark skin pigmentation, meaning these patients may be more hypoxic than the SpO2 reading suggests. Clinicians should consider this limitation and supplement SpO2 monitoring with clinical assessment and, where needed, ABG measurement. This is a recognised patient safety issue in current clinical practice.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000027', 'What is the evidence base for using oxygen in non-hypoxaemic palliative care patients with breathlessness?', 'Oxygen significantly reduces breathlessness in all palliative patients regardless of SpO2', 'Randomised controlled trial evidence shows no benefit of oxygen over air in reducing breathlessness in non-hypoxaemic palliative care patients', 'Oxygen is the first-line treatment for breathlessness in all palliative patients', 'Oxygen is contraindicated in palliative care', 'B', 'Multiple RCTs, including the MRC trial, have demonstrated that supplemental oxygen is no more effective than air in reducing the sensation of breathlessness in non-hypoxaemic patients with advanced illness. A fan directed at the face has stronger evidence for reducing breathlessness sensation. Oxygen should therefore be reserved for hypoxaemic palliative patients (SpO2 <90%) where symptom benefit can be demonstrated.')
